Description:
The Board Certified Behaviour Analyst (BCBA) will work as part of an inter-disciplinary central team to build capacity for various Hamilton-Wentworth Catholic District School Board (HWCDSB) staff in the development, implementation and in the maintaining of the principles of Applied Behaviour Analysis (ABA). In collaboration with the HWCDSB Student Support Services/Special
Education Central Resource Department, the role of the BCBA will include but is not limited to the following: conducting student functional behaviour assessments (FBA); reviewing, analyzing, interpreting data, and utilizing knowledge and data to contribute to developing student support plans; providing coaching opportunities and professional development sessions for building knowledge and in applying ABA strategies in an education setting; professional development sessions in conducting and applying results of functional behaviour assessments of students, for various HWCDSB staff, including but not limited to classroom teachers, program teachers, designated early childhood educators, educational assistants, school and system administrators, as well as, as required, to parents/guardians, and community members. The BCBA will act as a resource for school-based teams. In addition, the BCBA will lead and participate in various meetings, including school, parent, community, etc.; will write various reports including but not limited to board reports. The BCBA will also be responsible for ABA program development and for assessing and monitoring HWCDSB programs such as, but not limited to, the HWCDSB After Schools Skills Development Program for Students with ASD. The BCBA also will provide clinical supervision for positions such as ABA Facilitators.
ESSENTIAL FUNCTIONS: 
The following identifies the primary and essential functions of the position; it is not intended to be an exhaustive listing of all duties:

Develop and support the implementation of ABA strategies to address students’ learning and behavioural needs (Tier 2 and Tier 3 students);


Conduct, collect and analyze data, interpret and share results of formal assessments to understand functions of behavior, and recommend strategies;


Model and coach the implementation of student specific ABA strategies for classroom teachers and school teams (for Tier 1, Tier 2, Tier 3 students);


Develop, implement, and support implementation via coaching or modelling of student specific plans, e.g., student behavior plan;


Participate in case conferences and contribute to the development of the student Individual Education Plan (as appropriate);


Support data collection and analysis of data to make recommendations and monitor efficacy of implemented strategies for Tier 2 and Tier 3 students;


Collaborate and work closely with board, school, and community multi-disciplinary teams;


Participate and, where appropriate, lead various meetings, including but not limited to school, parent, board, community;


Support and coach school teams in the development of in-depth Functional Behaviour Assessments and Behaviour Support Plans for the purpose of providing a safe and effective educational environment for students with ASD who present with challenging behaviors and who are referred to student support services for applied behaviour analysis support;


Develop and provide professional development to school and system staff in the use of applied behaviour analysis strategies, functional behavioural assessments, and development and implementation of behaviour support plan for the classroom application;


Provide professional development to family and community members, as required;


Maintain and share current, evidence-based knowledge on ABA training, and research and practices;


Develop ABA evidence-based programming for the HWCDSB for students with ASD and for students with behavioural needs, based on data collection and analysis;


Create and present reports to board, school, and community groups and agencies, including but not limited to the HWCDSB Special Education Advisory Committee, the HWCDSB Board Committee, General Principals meetings, General Special Education Resource Teacher meetings, etc.;


Provide clinical supervision for ABA Facilitator who is working towards qualifying for the BCBA exam;


Participate in interviewing and selection of ABA Team members (e.g., BCBA, ABA Facilitator) positions;


Participate in the development of the HWCDSB Board Improvement Plan for Student Achievement;


Participate in monthly central team Managers meetings;


Supervise HWCDSB programs related to ABA;


Supervise the After School Skills Development Program (ASSDP) staff for their development and implementation of ABA strategies and/or board programs, e.g., ABA Facilitators, program supervisor, EAs, staff with RBT qualifications;


Supervise the implementation of activities and strategies in the ASSDP and/or board programs as well as monitor and provide direction in regards to effectiveness and impact;


Supervise the ASSDP program supervisors with respect to ABA responsibilities, e.g., collection and maintenance of data pertaining to ABA;


Perform related duties as required.

Qualifications:

Graduate degree in Psychology, ABA, Education or a related field;


Minimum 1 year of certification as a Board Certified Behaviour Analyst; and


Completed BACB approved 8-hour supervision training.

Preferred Experience and Skills:

Extensive knowledge of ABA and FBA;


Extensive experience working with and knowledge of school-aged children and young adults with ASD;


Clinical experience in behavior therapy, assessment, direct instruction and consultation regarding ABA;


Minimum 3 years of experience designing and implementing ABA programs for children with a diagnosis of Autism Spectrum Disorder;


Experience in developing and providing professional development training and information sessions related to the principles of ABA;


Excellent communication, interpersonal and teamwork skills;


Computer competency;


Excellent analytical skills;


Experience working in a school board.

